    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Why Should Schools Do a Parent's Job?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Evan Lerner letter on March 25 article on drug testing at New York City metropolitan area schools</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Is This the Answer to Drug Use?'' (March 25):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Is This the Answer to Drug Use?'' (March 25):</p>
        <p>I am 45-year-old parent with two children. Why are the schools doing more and more of my job as a parent? I don't need them to, and I don't want them to.</p>
        <p>If school officials think that testing is going to stop kids from drinking and doing drugs, then they are wrongly mistaken and their qualifications should be questioned. If kids want to experiment and engage, they will. At a minimum, the testing is just going to make the kids more rebellious and provide more stimulus for them to drink and do drugs.</p>
        <p>Who wants to bet me on the number of ''down with testing'' toasts to be raised over beers?</p>
        <p>The worst possible outcome of the testing is that kids will ''behave'' and build up their resentment throughout their high school years. Then when they reach college the shackles will be removed and they will overdo it.</p>
        <p>I'm an engaged parent, as all should be. I want to guide my kids through the trials and tribulations of as much as their lives as I can. Testing in school for alcohol and drugs takes that responsibility and privilege away from me. Don't do it.</p>
        <p>Evan Lerner  Mount Kisco</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
